{"question_id": "Q005", "question": "How do the encoder and decoder stacks differ in the Transformer architecture?", "ground_truth": "The encoder has repeated layers with self-attention and feed-forward sublayers, while the decoder adds an extra sublayer that attends over the encoder output and also uses masked self-attention so it cannot look ahead to future positions.", "category": "intra_paper_comparison", "difficulty": "medium", "policy": "maddpg_ceb", "data_source": "live_llm", "final_status": "accepted", "final_answer": "The encoder and decoder stacks in the Transformer architecture differ primarily in their structure and functionality. The encoder is composed of a stack of 6 identical layers, each having two sub-layers: a multi-head self-attention mechanism and a position-wise fully connected feed-forward network. In contrast, the decoder also consists of a stack of 6 identical layers, but it includes an additional third sub-layer that performs multi-head attention over the output of the encoder stack. This allows the decoder to incorporate information from the encoder's output while generating the output sequence.", "token_f1": 0.3617, "rouge_l": 0.2353, "correctness": 0.3617, "faithfulness": 1.0, "citation_support": 1.0, "source_precision": 0.3333, "source_recall": 1.0, "verification_pass": 1, "unsupported_claims": 0, "latency_seconds": 16.6698, "num_llm_calls": 3, "token_usage": 3799, "num_steps": 4, "trace": [{"step": 1, "agent": "retriever", "action": "hybrid_rerank", "params": {"dense_sparse_weight": 0.37182511389255524, "top_k": 21, "rerank_threshold": 0.422750860452652, "source_diversity": 0.4661089591681957}, "reward": -0.02, "done": false}, {"step": 2, "agent": "grader", "action": "loose_filter", "params": {"relevance_threshold": 0.6159060597419739, "evidence_keep_ratio": 0.5709900707006454, "strictness_score": 0.2256702482700348}, "reward": -0.07, "done": false}, {"step": 3, "agent": "generator", "action": "generate_short_answer", "params": {"tempe